metadata.name: Hyper Pixel #105
metadata.description:
Somewhere between pixel-art and axonometric architectural projections, spatial compositions assembled from multi-resolution pixel precise fragments. 

Hyper Pixel is the result of a continued interest in using projections to represent three dimensional object in  two dimensional picture image, and embracing the fact that all digital images are two dimensional arrays of discrete pixels. In that sense it is also a reaction against both skeuomorphism, or mimicking older media in digital form, and the push towards ever increasing fidelity and resolution. The project uses Military perspective, a form of oblique projection, or 45° - 45° axonometric projection, because these angels can approximated fittingly by square pixel grid. 

Press s, m, l, x for exporting an image with increasing resolution.
Press p for pause.
Press r for refresh.

Made with P5.js by @introspect0r

metadata.name: Trust #86
metadata.description:
Trust is an abstraction of the creative process, finding the line just before form becomes texture. Your experience with the painting requires trust; trust that something will appear from the chaos of the empty space, trust that the composition you imagine halfway through will evolve along with your ideas, and trust that the etchings lend a helping hand to the message of the piece. You may find yourself pulled left and right when decisions are made, and your interpretation at 25%, 50%, and 90% will all differ. This is what makes creating so fulfilling to me, a work of art can change course wildly from start to finish, ever molding itself until it enters the kiln.

Press ‘1’, ‘2’, or  ‘3’ to increase resolution (default is 1, higher than default may not work on certain browsers. Successfully testing in Chrome, Brave, and Opera GX with hardware acceleration enabled)

Click or tap to zoom to full res (exact zoom depends on your display)
Press ’s’ to save a .png
Press ’t’ to toggle brush texture

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Spring will be back again  #72
metadata.description:
This project aims to capture the essence of the Japanese hanami experience where people gather to admire the fleeting beauty of the cherry blossom.

It's a representation of the beauty of an unreal nature where the details of the leaves and flowers are imaginary and always different.

While some trees in the animation are depicted in full bloom with delicate petals and lush leaves, other may yet have to blossom or may already have lost their blooms, or even don't have leaves or flowers at all.

Crafted entirely with lines of code in vanilla javascript, without the use of reference images or templates.

There are over 20 distinct features that define each token and the animation is also interactive

Each time the animation is played, it generates a unique and dynamic display of the blossom trees, while still maintaining the features defined by the underlying token.

You may also change the resolution or the layout at any time, or toggle the animation mode.



Commands

[1] Low resolution
[2] Normal resolution
[3] High res
[4] Super high res
[5] Print res (not animated)

[a] or [space] Reload in animation mode
[s] Reload in static mode
[d] Download snapshot in current resolution

Change layout:

[z] 1x2.5 (Portrait)
[x] 1x2
[c] 1x1.5 (default in mobile)
[v] 1x1 Square
[b] 1.5x1 (Landscape, default in desktop)
[n] 2x1
[m] 2.5x1

May be unresponsive on higher resolutions (in those cases turning off the animation mode is recommended)

metadata.name: Kyma #14
metadata.description:
Kyma (/kee-ma/, κύμα) is a Greek word meaning wave. It is my exploration of an acoustic phenomenon known as ‘Chladni Patterns’. 

Ernst Florens Friedrich Chladni was a German physicist and musician. He was a pioneer of modern acoustics and made numerous contributions to the field. Chladni's work had a significant influence on the development of modern music theory and the technology of musical instruments. In 1787, Chladni was trying to understand how sound waves propagate and interact with objects. By vibrating a metal plate and sprinkling sand on it, he observed that the sand arranged itself into distinct patterns. These patterns are created due to the interaction between the sound waves and the plate: the sound waves cause the plate to vibrate, which in turn causes the sand to move. The sand will move away from areas of high vibration and towards areas of low vibration. This creates a unique pattern of ridges, circles, and many other shapes.

Kyma continues this study by adding color, light, and composition to the equation. Each iteration is a unique combination of two Chladni plates with different characteristics, accompanied by a palette, background lighting, and variational drawing algorithm. Plates interact with each other, forming patterns from the small detailed net-like grid to megalithic sculptures of unknown creatures and windows to another worlds.

Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Rendering can be computationally heavy, please be patient and give it some time to draw.
Chrome is highly recommended for live mode and high res saving.

Made with love, math, and p5js. 

Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2400 x 1600
[2] - save PNG 4800 x 3200
[3] - save PNG 9600 x 6400
[4] - save PNG 14400 x 9600

metadata.name: CMYK:Unchecked #51
metadata.description:
CMYK:Unchecked offers almost infinite canvases designed to challenge the concept and state of being unverified.

Layout variations include 80 / 40 / 20 / 10 / 5 / 4 / 1 circles. 
Each circle presented is either Cyan, Magento, Yellow or Black.

---

This work is of course a parody of 'Checks' by Jack Butcher presented in a transformative way. The work is in no way related to the original 'Checks' work and is not intended to fool anyone into thinking so thus does not affect the originals market or value.

metadata.name: Element #203
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Modulacions 2: 'Memory' (audio) #53
metadata.description:
"Modulacions 2: Memory" ies the second piece of the series 'Modulations'. Shorter (at most 12 characters of the Fxhash string) but with memory that is displayed on the screen.

Modulacions (Modulations): modulation with an oscillator (carrier) with an LFO (modulator).

-The LFO is controlled by some of fxhash characters

-Some parameters are randomly assigned to each of the possible characters of the fxhash string (0,1,2....X,Y,Z): carrier frequency, maximum and minimum frequencies of the modulator, waveforms, views etc.

-A number of fxhash characters are selected (4,6,8 or 12), and in order they are played and displayed using the assigned values.

-Each character is encoded in binary-> the LFO frequency is controlled: 1->maximum frequency, 0->minimum frequency.

Features:
·dark: black (true) or white (false).
·carrier_wave: wave shape of carrier oscillator (sine, square, triangle or sawtooth)
·modulator_mult: value of LFO multiplier.
·modulator_sum: value added to LFO amplitude.
·num_fxhash_chars: number of fxhash characters used (4, 6 , 8 or 12)
·carrier_freq_range: frequency range of carrier (low, mid or high).
·frames_per_bit: duration of each bit in frames.(10, 15 or 20)
·one_visual: same visual for all chars (true) or nor (false).

Press 's' to save canvas as png.

-NOTES:
·Headphones recomended. Some extreme sounds (frequency and amplitude) can be generated.
·Preview is randomly generated, the final result can be very different.

-p5js and p5.sound

metadata.name: System β #42
metadata.description:
α -> β is about "Increases in magnitude and decreases in computation". And still related the fleeting time in the generating process.

My role in this work is more of a discoverer than a creator. 

Try to reveal the possibilities of time perception in the generative art through negotiating with incomprehensible mathematical equations.

What I want to explore through this work is that behind the generated results, the dynamic process of generations are equally diverse and unpredictable.

When we watch the generating process displayed on the computer, changing instantly, moving, multiplying, disappearing, and we hesitate, wonder, pause, await, as if many possibilities of time perception have emerged in the fragmented moments.

_
press [1] -> β 
press [2] -> β⁰　 
press [3] -> β¹
-
Press [s] in live view to save as PNG.
Press [d] in live view to save as hi-res PNG.
-
If you need your collection in SVG format, feel free to DM me.

metadata.name: Stuck Inside #46
metadata.description:
As Spring transitions to Summer, flowers are in full bloom. With no outside view from my desk, I find myself daydreaming of walks around the yard, watering flowers, and watching the insects.

This is a simple and abstract kinetic piece that represents the daydreams I have while working, as I look forward to my next break, when I can walk outside for a few minutes.

100% of secondary sale royalties will go to the Processing Foundation.

The piece is responsive and will adapt to your browser window size. Press SPACE to export a high-resolution PNG image of the current frame at the current aspect ratio. 

If you are using Safari, the animation will be rate limited until you click or tap once on the piece.
